Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Pop a #saucepan{} of water with @salt{0.5%tsp} onto boil for the potatoes. Peel the @potatoes{450%g} and slice into rounds ½cm thick. Trim the root and dark green part from the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways then thinly slice widthways. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated). Trim the @green beans{80%g} and chop in half. Pick the @rosemary{1%sprig} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks). Add the potato to the pan and simmer until tender, ~{10-12%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a splash of oil in another pan on medium heat. Add the leek, half the rosemary and a pinch of salt. Cook, stirring, until the leeks are soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}. Stir in the @creme fraiche{150%g} and bring to a simmer. Remove from the heat. When the potatoes are cooked, drain, then add to the leeks. Turn carefully to coat. Spoon into an appropriate sized #ovenproof dish{}.

Sprinkle the @crumbled blue cheese{60%g} on top of the gratin and bake in the oven until golden and bubbly ~{12-15%minutes}. Meanwhile, heat a splash of oil in a large #frying pan{} over medium high heat. Season the @lamb loin{2}(trimmed) with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} and sprinkle over the remaining rosemary. Brown the meat on all sides, ~{2%minutes} and then transfer to a #baking tray{}. Roast on the middle shelf for ~{9-10%minutes}. Keep the pan we will use it again later.

Whilst everything is in the oven, rinse the potato pan pop the @red wine stock paste{28%g} into it with the @water{150%ml}(for the sauce) and put onto medium heat. Stir to dissolve the stock pot and then simmer until thickened and glossy, about ~{10%minutes}.

When the lamb is ready, wrap loosely in #foil{} and allow to rest for ~{5%minutes}. Meanwhile, heat the frying pan over medium heat (add a splash of oil if necessary). Stir fry the green beans until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Add a splash of water as they cook. Add the @baby spinach{100%g} and cook until wilted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season well with salt and pepper and then use a #spoon{} to squeeze out any excess water from the spinach. Get ready to serve!

Heat your sauce through gently before serving if needed. Arrange the green beans and spinach on your plate. Thinly slice the lamb loins and sit on top of the greens. Serve a generous amount of the gratin alongside and spoon the sauce over the meat and around the plate. Enjoy!

> This Rosemary Scented Lamb Loin is bursting full of flavours and make the perfect dinner
> night option, perfect for a fresh start!